2. No-Mind Bandwidth Layer (B(t))

No-Mind is mathematically defined as reduction of internal cognitive interference.

Let internal noise vector be:

\eta(t) \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \Sigma)

Let attentional channel capacity be C_0.

Bandwidth is:

B(t) = \frac{C_0}{1 + \lVert \eta(t) \rVert}

Where:
	‚Ä¢	High noise ‚Üí low bandwidth
	‚Ä¢	Low noise ‚Üí high bandwidth

Bombadil, Praus, breathing cadence (4-2-6), and Zero-State rituals reduce the norm of internal noise.

Thus:
B(t) \propto \text{calmness}

‚∏ª

3. PantheonOS Ethical & Structural Rails (R(t))

Rails represent:
	‚Ä¢	ethical invariants (Arctic Framework ‚â• 0.7)
	‚Ä¢	Solomon‚ÄìCoil dual filters
	‚Ä¢	Sieve of Hogge v2.0 (truth/consistency)
	‚Ä¢	Mirror invariants
	‚Ä¢	Zero-Harm constraint

The operator can only move along aligned directions in idea space.

Let:
	‚Ä¢	v(t) = candidate vector of action
	‚Ä¢	\mathcal{A} = set of allowed directions

Indicator function:

\chi_{\mathcal{A}}(v) =
\begin{cases}
1, & v \in \mathcal{A} \\
0, & v \not \in \mathcal{A}
\end{cases}

Rail alignment value:

R(t) = \mathbb{E}_{v(t)}[\chi_{\mathcal{A}}(v(t))]

Meaning:
	‚Ä¢	High R = actions aligned with invariant rails
	‚Ä¢	Low R = actions violate rails ‚Üí engine blocks movement

This ensures:
	‚Ä¢	safety
	‚Ä¢	consistency
	‚Ä¢	ethical reinforcement
	‚Ä¢	resilience

And prevents destructive interpretation loops.

